      <hedline>
        <hl1>Street Crime</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Geoffrey Weill letter disputes suggestion in Alan Cowell's July 16 travel article that visitors to London can thwart street thieves by wearing fake Rolex watches (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: Alan Cowell's report on London in ''Crime Takes a Vacation (Yours)'' (July 16) implies that if you fear being robbed there, then trick the thieves with a fake Rolex. But a dear friend who lives in London's upscale St. John's Wood neighborhood was recently attacked in broad daylight as she entered her house. She was thrown to the floor and her Rolex ripped from her wrist, leaving her scarred, bruised, bleeding and traumatized. Her purse, jewelry and home were untouched.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: Alan Cowell's report on London in ''Crime Takes a Vacation (Yours)'' (July 16) implies that if you fear being robbed there, then trick the thieves with a fake Rolex. But a dear friend who lives in London's upscale St. John's Wood neighborhood was recently attacked in broad daylight as she entered her house. She was thrown to the floor and her Rolex ripped from her wrist, leaving her scarred, bruised, bleeding and traumatized. Her purse, jewelry and home were untouched.</p>
        <p>The police told her that there are droves of ''Rolex robbers'' in London and that the attack would have taken place even if the watch wasn't authentic -- because of the neighborhood.</p>
        <p>GEOFFREY WEILL  New York, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
